# API Design

Coding patterns for backend APIs. IF your project has an API, apply these patterns. Applies to REST, GraphQL, or RPC - REST is the default assumption.

> All numeric values in this file are `[DEFAULT]` - adjust per project.

---

## Stack split

- **REST:** URL rules below apply to HTTP paths.
- **GraphQL / RPC:** Verbs live in schema/operations - not in REST path segments.

---

## URL Structure

**Nesting preference:** Default flat paths. **One** sub-resource segment under a collection is preferred (e.g. `/items/{id}/members`). Deeper nesting only when parent-child identity requires it in the path - not for folder convenience.

- **Plural nouns** for resources: `/api/users`, `/api/records`
- **kebab-case** for multi-word: `/api/activity-logs`, `/api/settings`
- **Nested resources** for relationships: `/api/campaigns/{id}/members`
- **Never verbs in URLs** - HTTP methods already carry the verb. Adding a verb to the path is always redundant or wrong.

```
METHOD   PATH                  MEANING
GET      /api/items            list
POST     /api/items            create
GET      /api/items/{id}       read one
PUT      /api/items/{id}       full replace
PATCH    /api/items/{id}       partial update
DELETE   /api/items/{id}       remove
```

**Verb exception - operation sub-paths:** Allowed only when ALL three conditions are true:
1. The operation cannot be expressed with a standard HTTP method on the resource (it is not create/read/update/delete)
2. The operation has no persistent resource representation - you cannot `GET` its result later
3. The sub-path name is an **operation-type noun or hyphenated compound**, not a bare verb

```
ALLOWED (operation nouns - meet all 3 conditions):
  POST /api/assets/bulk-archive     <- compound noun describing the operation type
  POST /api/emails/force-sync       <- compound noun, no persistent result to GET
  POST /api/sessions/bulk-close     <- compound noun on a collection

Operation nouns (meet all 3 conditions - includes export-style compounds when naming the operation type):
  POST /api/exports/run             <- noun compound for an export job (illustration)

BANNED (bare verbs - fail condition 3):
  POST /api/assets/export           <- bare verb alone; prefer noun compound for the operation type
  POST /api/users/{id}/resend       <- bare verb; use noun: /api/users/{id}/invitation-resend or fold into PATCH
  POST /api/logs/{id}/revert        <- bare verb; use noun: /api/logs/{id}/reversion
  POST /api/assets/import           <- bare verb; use noun: /api/assets/imports (POST to start, GET to check status)

BANNED (verbs disguised as anything):
  /api/getUsers    /api/createRecord    /api/deleteAll    <- always wrong regardless of method
```

