## Response Shapes

### Success Responses

Return the data directly by default. An envelope wrapper (`{ data, meta }`) is acceptable when you need to include tracing IDs, API versions, or partial error information alongside the response.

```
GET /api/resources
-> 200: [{ "id": "...", "name": "..." }, ...]

POST /api/resources
-> 201: { "id": "...", "name": "..." }

DELETE /api/resources/{id}
-> 200: { "deleted": true }

Note: Use "id" in API responses regardless of database convention (_id for MongoDB, id for SQL). Map at the boundary (see code-patterns.md, Data Transformation Pattern).
```

### Error Responses

Default: `{ "error": "Human-readable summary" }` with proper HTTP status. For forms with multiple fields, use `{ "error": "Validation failed", "fields": { "email": "Required", "name": "Too short" } }` to support field-level error display.

```
401: { "error": "Unauthorized" }
403: { "error": "You do not have permission to perform this action." }
400: { "error": "Email is required." }
404: { "error": "Resource not found." }
409: { "error": "A record with this value already exists." }
422: { "error": "Cannot delete a record with active references." }
500: { "error": "An unexpected error occurred." }
```

### NEVER do this:

```
200: { "success": false, "error": "Something failed" }
```

Use proper HTTP status codes. A 200 means success - don't return errors with 200 status.

