## Status Code Reference

**Principle:** Use HTTP status codes semantically - the status code alone should tell the client what category of result occurred.

[REFERENCE] Common status codes and when to use them:

| Code | When to Use |
|------|-------------|
| 200 | Successful read, update, or delete |
| 201 | Successful creation |
| 400 | Invalid input (missing fields, wrong format) |
| 401 | Not authenticated (no session / expired token) |
| 403 | Authenticated but not authorized (insufficient permissions) |
| 404 | Resource does not exist |
| 409 | Conflict (duplicate unique field, version mismatch) |
| 422 | Valid syntax but semantically wrong (business rule violation) |
| 429 | Rate limited (too many requests) |
| 500 | Unexpected server error (log it, don't expose details) |

